The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, April 08, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, April 7: With the income tax department serving a demand notice on IT majors, including Wipro, Nasscom today said it has taken up the issue with the government and hoped it would be resolved soon. While the issue had arisen due to different interpretations of the existing rules under sections 10a and 10b of the IT Act that allows for a 10-year tax holiday, Nasscom president Kiran Karnik said, We do not want to let regulation drive policy. 																								 Mumbai, April 7: The rupee closed at 43.53 per dollar today, registering a gain of 21 paise over Tuesdays close. The rise was propelled by robust trade and foreign capital investment inflows.																								 Mumbai, April 7: The Reserve Bank today got a good response for the auction of 91-day treasury bills of Rs 2,000 crore even as it has announced sale of 6.18 per cent government stock of Rs 5,000 crore tomorrow under the market stabilisation scheme.																								 New Delhi, April 7: Softer interest rate regime and a boom in the housing, retail and infrastructure sectors boosted bank credits by Rs 1,19,684 crore last fiscal. Reserve Bank governor Y. V. Reddy said, Credit expansion in 2003-04 appears to have been led by the housing and retail sectors.																								 New Delhi, April 7: Radico Khaitan has acquired Andhra Pradesh-based Anab-E-Shahi bottling plant and plans to add eight more units to its portfolio.																								.
